## QUESTION TEXT
A travel agent records the duration and cost of the 15 flights he sold on one day. The data for the first 13 flights are plotted on the scatter diagram. [Diagram: A scatter diagram plotted on a Cartesian grid. The x-axis is labeled 'Duration (minutes)' and ranges from 0 to 250 with major grid lines every 50 units. The y-axis is labeled 'Cost (£)' and ranges from 0 to 160 with major grid lines every 20 units. Thirteen cross markers ('x') are plotted at approximately the following coordinates: (50, 55), (60, 75), (70, 70), (95, 95), (105, 98), (120, 85), (130, 110), (140, 92), (150, 112), (160, 102), (180, 115), (220, 65), (240, 155).]

a) The data for the final two flights is: The following table: Duration 210 minutes, 1 hour 40 minutes. Cost £130, £80. Plot these flights on the scatter diagram.

b) The cost of one of the 15 flights had been discounted in a sale. Circle the most likely flight on the scatter diagram.

ci) Draw a line of best fit on the scatter diagram.

cii) Use your line of best fit to estimate the duration of a flight costing £90.

d) Explain why the travel agent should not use his records to estimate the cost of a 7 hour flight.

## MARKING SCHEME
- B1: 100 soi or for one point plotted correctly. Half square tolerance. May be implied by point plotted at duration 100 
- B1: Points plotted at (210, 130) and (100, 80) 
- A1: Point at (220, 64) circled (Use overlay anchored on top right point)
- A1: Ruled line of best fit drawn (Line must reach to edges of overlay)
- A1: Their line used to give duration for £90 ± 5 minutes (Strict FT from their intended straight line of best fit. NB read (n, 90) not (90, n))
- A1: [7 hours is] is beyond the given data oe (Accept eg the trend may not continue)

